{"text": "From Majorana fermions to topological quantum computation in\n\nsemiconductor/superconductor heterostructures\n\nJay D. Sau1 and Sumanta Tewari2\n\n1Department of Physics, Condensed Matter\n\nTheory Center and the Joint Quantum Institute,\n\nUniversity of Maryland, College Park, Maryland 20742, USA\n\n2Department of Physics and Astronomy,\n\nClemson University, Clemson, SC 29634, USA\n\n(Dated: May 11, 2021)\n\n1\n\narXiv:2105.03769v1 [cond-mat.supr-con] 8 May 2021\n\nI.\n\nINTRODUCTION\n\nDirac is reported to have remarked in one of his talks that his equation was more intelli-\n\ngent than its author. But, as noted by Victor Weisskopf1, it must be added that it was Dirac\n\nhimself who found most of the additional insights. The concept of Majorana fermion, which\n\nalso followed from the Dirac equation and was developed by Ettore Majorana2, was a notable\n\nexception. In relativistic quantum mechanics, physics of spin\u20131/2 fermions is described by\n\nthe Dirac equation3,4,\n\n(i\u03b3\u03bc\u2202\u03bc \u2212m)\u03c8 = 0.\n\n(1)\n\nHere, we have used the natural units (\u0127= c = 1), and \u03b3\u03bc, with \u03bc = 0, 1, 2, 3, are a set of\n\nmatrices satisfying the algebra,\n\n{\u03b3\u03bc, \u03b3\u03bd} \u2261\u03b3\u03bc\u03b3\u03bd + \u03b3\u03bd\u03b3\u03bc = 2\u03b7\u03bc\u03bd,\n\n(2)\n\nwhere \u03b7\u03bc\u03bd is the Minkowski metric (\u03b7\u03bc\u03bd = 0, \u03bc \u0338= \u03bd; \u03b700 = 1; \u03b7ii = \u22121, i = 1, 2, 3), and\n\n\u03b30\u03b3\u03bc\u03b30 = \u03b3\u2020\n\n\u03bc\n\n(3)\n\nEq. 2 follows from the requirement that the energy eigenvalues satisfy the condition E2 =\n\np2+m2, while Eq. 3 ensures hermiticity of Dirac Hamiltonian HD that follows from re-casting\n\nof Eq. 1 in terms of Schrodinger equation\n\ni\u2202\u03c8\n\n\u2202t = HD\u03c8;\n\nHD = \u2212i\u03b30\u20d7\u03b3 \u00b7 \u20d7\u2207+ \u03b30m.\n\n(4)\n\nIn (3 + 1) dimension, the simplest representation of the Clifford algebra in Eqs. 2,3 can be\n\nfound in terms of four 4 \u00d7 4 matrices \u03b3\u03bc, known as Dirac matrices. There are infinitely\n\nmany unitarily equivalent representations of the Dirac matrices, each constituting a basis\n\nfor solving the Dirac equation in Eq.", "embedding": [0.01050787, -0.008673261, 0.021102598, -0.010865216, 0.032482695, -0.019452764, -0.0132586565, -0.026330983, -0.07909352, 0.08829402, 0.058205012, -0.019257933, -0.003918118, -0.05456334, -0.032926258, -0.006322735, 0.000539088, -0.03626953, -0.056842793, 0.018170092, 0.05530641, 0.022505628, -0.025138382, -0.011730543, -0.013455949, 0.039505865, 0.04142377, 0.03294863, 0.038272962, 0.035745133, 0.03928985, -0.025345512, 0.023962442, -0.018952975, -7.942381e-05, 0.021208683, -0.002991094, -0.028587842, 0.0369117, -0.00093269633, 0.04145482, -0.018013807, 0.001971858, -0.030315317, -0.021444026, 0.021051768, -0.0058618514, 0.01889896, -0.005488253, -0.09324944, -0.009895505, -0.026485858, 0.011616741, 0.010570608, 0.007562889, -0.01633739, 0.0069368677, 0.0051079635, -0.021592606, -0.009794705, 0.0056395605, -0.03117032, 0.020900607, -0.047766265, 0.01852355, 0.041871503, -0.018456953, 0.047420245, -0.018965103, -0.0526185, -0.0038522833, -0.012006789, -0.012090046, 0.008285029, -0.046538528, 0.01731034, 0.013235282, -0.03400937, -0.08299378, 0.012131606, -0.0012901798, 0.014753716, -0.04639135, 0.03623281, -0.0038278033, -0.044350874, 0.0035467197, 0.0051220343, -0.0129007185, -0.020326344, 0.021049412, 0.039987545, 0.009205678, 0.0057643615, 0.05350446, 0.01624568, -0.028238202, 0.033608675, 0.012169687, -0.0019479906, 0.0056050075, 0.091821164, 0.0052886214, 0.0673968, -0.055312276, 0.061308753, 2.6890155e-05, 0.009846838, 0.01799289, -0.059698388, 0.05259705, 0.012641271, 0.01484896, 0.023342231, 0.00960371, 0.04007485, 0.014983026, 0.016486503, -0.036682885, 0.0058892, 0.0071243965, -0.021590771, 0.056066263, 0.018687002, -0.017386466, -0.014687266, 0.00091782806, 0.032615844, -0.018871997, 0.025119668, 0.028123569, 0.0148